supermassive black holes at the centers of galaxies.
JWST is also equipped to study the formation of stars and planetary systems. By observing star-
forming regions in great detail, the telescope can provide new information about how stars and planets
form and evolve. This could lead to a better understanding of how our own solar system came into
existence.
One of the most exciting possibilities is that the JWST could detect evidence of life beyond Earth. The
telescope is capable of studying the atmospheres of exoplanets (planets that orbit stars outside our solar
system). By analyzing the light that passes through these atmospheres, JWST can detect the presence of
certain chemicals, such as water vapor, methane, and carbon dioxide, which may indicate the potential
for life. While this is not a direct search for alien civilizations, it could provide the first signs that
habitable worlds exist elsewhere in the universe.
The Scientific History Leading to JWST's Development
The development of the James Webb Space Telescope builds on decades of advances in both space
technology and our understanding of the universe. The idea for a large space telescope like JWST first
gained traction in the 1990s, following the incredible success of the Hubble Space Telescope.
Launched in 1990, Hubble fundamentally transformed our view of the universe by providing
unprecedentedly clear images of distant galaxies, nebulae, and other astronomical phenomena.
However, while Hubble made enormous contributions to science, its design was limited in several
ways, particularly when it came to observing infrared light.
Infrared astronomy became increasingly important in the late 20th century as scientists realized that
many of the most interesting phenomena in the universe, such as star formation and the behavior of
distant galaxies, could only be studied effectively in infrared wavelengths. The development of more
sensitive infrared detectors, along with improvements in mirror technology and space observatory
design, eventually made the concept of a new, large infrared telescope feasible.
In 1996, NASA officially began planning for what would eventually become the James Webb Space
Telescope. Originally, the project was envisioned as the Next Generation Space Telescope (NGST) and
was designed to be the successor to Hubble. Over the next two decades, the telescope went through
numerous design iterations and faced many technical challenges, including delays and budget overruns.
Despite these difficulties, the project continued to receive support from NASA, the European Space
Agency (ESA), and the Canadian Space Agency (CSA), all of which contributed to its development.
One of the most challenging aspects of building JWST was designing its enormous, segmented mirror
and the complex sunshield that would keep the telescope cold enough to function properly. Both
components had to be folded up to fit inside the rocket that launched the telescope into space and then
successfully deployed once JWST reached its destination. This process involved intricate engineering
and extensive testing to ensure everything would work correctly, given that the telescope could not be
repaired once it was in space, unlike Hubble, which received multiple servicing missions from the
Space Shuttle.
